{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"aa3da9ef-39af-4be1-ae59-9b122a1d2a7b","content":"Use conditional compilation with `#if` directives in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.IosNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\nEach platform implementation goes under `Platforms/<platform>/` and is only compiled for its target. The symbols (`ANDROID`, `IOS`, `WINDOWS`) are defined automatically by the MAUI SDK based on the target framework.\n\n**Key points:**\n- Place each implementation in its respective `Platforms/` folder so it's only compiled for that platform.\n- No fallback is needed — MAUI always builds for a specific platform, so exactly one branch compiles.\n- If you want a shared fallback, add `#else` with a no-op implementation.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"363cff6b-0233-43a0-bb7e-5698baa76899","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection — specifically how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"DC0F:1909B6:1E96240:22D4E3D:69F54CCF"},"id":"ae6ef682-0ae4-4785-9179-5b54ed9d446b","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:01:12.899Z","parentId":"47b93009-c5a8-4507-b7e6-f5974cbcc256"}
